# This is just a convenience function for plotting things.
def plot_phase_portrait(matrices,titles):
    """Makes a plot of the phase portraits of the given matrices"""
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, len(matrices), figsize=(5*len(matrices)+1,5),squeeze=False)
    
    x1,x2 = np.meshgrid(np.linspace(-1, 1, 9),np.linspace(-1, 1, 9))
    
    for i,[matrix,title] in enumerate(zip(matrices,titles)):
        a = np.array(matrix).astype(np.float64)
        x1dot = a[0,0]*x1 + a[0,1]*x2 # x1'(t) = a11 * x1 + a12 * x2
        x2dot = a[1,0]*x1 + a[1,1]*x2  # x2'(t) = a21 * x1 + a22 * x2
        ax[0,i].quiver(x1, x2, x1dot, x2dot, color='r')
        ax[0,i].set_xlabel('$x_1$')
        ax[0,i].set_ylabel('$x_2$')
        ax[0,i].set_title(title)
    return None

1. Phase Portraits and Linearization (10pts)¶

For each of the following systems, (i) find the equilibria, (ii) linearize the system around each equilibrium and find the eigenvalues and eigenvectors, (iii) state whether the system is stable at each equilibrium, (iv) draw a phase portrait by first drawing the phase portrait near the equilibria and then interpolating. Compare your drawing to a phase portrait of the entire system generated with Python.

$$ \mathrm{a)} \;\; \begin{pmatrix} \dot x_1 \\ \dot x_2 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} x_2^2 \\ x_1^2 \end{pmatrix} $$$$ \mathrm{b)} \;\; \begin{pmatrix} \dot x_1 \\ \dot x_2 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} x_1^2 + x_2^2 \\ x_2 \end{pmatrix} $$$$ \mathrm{c)} \;\; \begin{pmatrix} \dot x_1 \\ \dot x_2 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} \sin x_2 \\ \cos x_1 \end{pmatrix} $$

$\textbf{Grading breakdown:}$

2.5pts for finding the equilibria of (a),(b),(c)
2.5pts for linearizing the system around each equilibrium and finding the eigenvalues and eigenvectors for (a),(b),(c)
2.5pts for stating whether the system is stable at each equilibrium for (a),(b),(c)
2.5pts for generating a phase portrait for (a),(b),(c)

1.a)

We consider the system $$ \begin{pmatrix} \dot x_1 \\ \dot x_2 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} x_2^2 \\ x_1^2 \end{pmatrix}. $$

The dynamics have a fixed point (i.e. equilibrium point), $\bar x = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$. So we will linearize about this $\bar x$:

$$ \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} \biggr\rvert_{x = \bar x} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{\partial (x_2^2)}{\partial x_1} & \frac{\partial (x_2^2)}{\partial x_2} \\ \frac{\partial (x_1^2)}{\partial x_1} & \frac{\partial (x_1^2)}{\partial x_2} \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 2x_2 \\ 2x_1 & 0 \end{pmatrix} \biggr\rvert_{x = \bar x} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix} $$

This system has repeated eigenvalues, $\lambda_1 = \lambda_2 = 0$, and linearly independent eigenvectors:

$$v_1 = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} \text{, } v_2 = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}.$$

Since $\lambda=0$ this system is marginally stable. Here, all solutions are constants. Moreover, since $\frac{\dot x_2}{\dot x_1} = \frac{0}{0}$ the phase portrait is not well defined.

1.b)

We consider the system $$ \begin{pmatrix} \dot x_1 \\ \dot x_2 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} x_1^2 + x_2^2 \\ x_2 \end{pmatrix}. $$

The dynamics have a fixed point, $\bar x = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$. So we will linearize about this $\bar x$:

$$ \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} \biggr\rvert_{x = \bar x} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{\partial (x_1^2 + x_2^2)}{\partial x_1} & \frac{\partial (x_1^2 + x_2^2)}{\partial x_2} \\ \frac{\partial (x_2)}{\partial x_1} & \frac{\partial (x_2)}{\partial x_2} \end{pmatrix}\biggr\rvert_{x = \bar x} = \begin{pmatrix} 2x_1 & 2x_2 \\ 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix} \biggr\rvert_{x = \bar x} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix} $$

This system has distinct eigenvalues, $\lambda_1 =0, \lambda_2 = 1$, which implies marginally stablity. It has linearly independent eigenvectors:

$$v_1 = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} \text{, } v_2 = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}.$$

(Note that the axes given by the eigenvectors greatly helps us determine the phase portrait intuitively.)

1.c)

We consider the system:

$$ \begin{pmatrix} \dot x_1 \\ \dot x_2 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} \sin x_2 \\ \cos x_1 \end{pmatrix}. $$

The dynamics have periodic fixed points, $\bar x_n = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{\pi}{2} + n\pi \\ n\pi \end{pmatrix}$ for $n\in\mathbb{Z}$. So we will linearize about this general $\bar x_n$:

$$ \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} \biggr\rvert_{x = \bar x} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{\partial (\sin{(x_2)})}{\partial x_1} & \frac{\partial (\sin{(x_2)})}{\partial x_2} \\ \frac{\partial (\cos{(x_1)})}{\partial x_1} & \frac{\partial (\cos{(x_1)})}{\partial x_2} \end{pmatrix}\biggr\rvert_{x = \bar x} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & \cos{(x_2)} \\ -\sin{(x_1)} & 0 \end{pmatrix} \biggr\rvert_{x = \bar x} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & \cos{(n\pi)} \\ -\sin{(\frac{\pi}{2} + n\pi)} & 0 \end{pmatrix} $$$$\implies A = \pm \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ -1 & 0 \end{pmatrix} $$

This system has distinct eigenvalues, $\lambda_1 = -i, \lambda_2 = i$, which are stable and unstable, respectively.

Case 1 ($n=0$ or is even): It has linearly independent eigenvectors:

$$v_1 = \begin{pmatrix} i \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} \text{, } v_2 = \begin{pmatrix} -i \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}.$$

Case 2 ($n$ is odd): It has linearly independent eigenvectors:

$$v_1 = \begin{pmatrix} -i \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} \text{, } v_2 = \begin{pmatrix} i \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}.$$

2. Nonlinear Systems (10pts)¶

a) Find a single nonlinear systems that has exactly four distinct equilibria, each of which has a different eigenvalue structure (i.e. a different type in the taxonomy).

b) Find a nonlinear system that has the following phase portrait. Hint: Try polar coordinates. Plot the phase portait in Python.

$\textbf{Grading breakdown:}$

3pts for finding a nonlinear system that has 4 distinct equilibria
1pt per different eigenvalue structure shown (up to 4pts total)
2pts for finding a nonlinear system that has a limit cycle at r=1, and for r!=1 the trajectories spiral toward r=1
1pt for plotting the phase portrait

Eigenvalue structures

$\bullet$ Real, distinct: $\begin{cases} \lambda_1,\lambda_2>0 \implies \text{Unstable node}\\ \lambda_1,\lambda_2<0 \implies \text{Stable node}\\ \text{one positive, one negative} \implies \text{Saddle point}\end{cases}$

$\bullet$ Real, repeated: $\begin{cases} \text{two LI eigenvectors} \implies \text{Singular node (could be stable or not)}\\ \text{one LI eigenvector} \implies \text{Degenerate node (could be stable or not)} \end{cases}$

$\bullet$ Real, one zero eigenvalue $\implies$ Marginally stable

$\bullet$ Complex: $\begin{cases} Re(\lambda)<0 \implies \text{Stable focus (i.e. a sprial going toward the center node)} \\ Re(\lambda)>0 \implies \text{Unstable focus (i.e. a sprial going away the center node)} \\ Re(\lambda)=0 \implies \text{Center node in which the trajectories are circles/ellipses} \end{cases}$

2.a)

Consider the system

$$ \begin{pmatrix} \dot x_1 \\ \dot x_2 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} x_1(1-x_1-x_2) \\ 2x_2(1 - \frac{1}{2}x_2 - \frac{3}{2}x) \end{pmatrix}. $$

The dynamics have four fixed points:

$$\bar x_{e1} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix},\bar x_{e2} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix},\bar x_{e3} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix},\bar x_{e4} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{1}{2} \\ \frac{1}{2} \end{pmatrix}.$$

So we will linearize about each $\bar x_{ei}$:

$$ J = \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{\partial (x_1(1-x_1-x_2))}{\partial x_1} & \frac{\partial (x_1(1-x_1-x_2))}{\partial x_2} \\ \frac{\partial (2x_2(1 - \frac{1}{2}x_2 - \frac{3}{2}x))}{\partial x_1} & \frac{\partial (2x_2(1 - \frac{1}{2}x_2 - \frac{3}{2}x))}{\partial x_2} \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} (1-2x_1-x_2) & -x_1 \\ -3x_2 & (2-2x_2-3x_1) \end{pmatrix} $$

At the first fixed point we see,

$$ A_1 = J(0,0) = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 2 \end{pmatrix} \implies \begin{cases} \lambda_1 = 1 \\ \lambda_2 = 2 \end{cases}. $$

At the second fixed point we see,

$$ A_2 = J(0,2) = \begin{pmatrix} -1 & 0 \\ -6 & -2 \end{pmatrix} \implies \begin{cases} \lambda_1 = -2 \\ \lambda_2 = -1 \end{cases}. $$

At the third fixed point we see,

$$ A_3 = J(1,0) = \begin{pmatrix} -1 & -1 \\ 0 & -1 \end{pmatrix} \implies \begin{cases} \lambda_1 = -1 \\ \lambda_2 = -1 \end{cases}. $$

At the last fixed point we see,

$$ A_4 = J(\frac{1}{2},\frac{1}{2}) = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{-1}{2} & \frac{-1}{2} \\ \frac{-3}{2} & \frac{-1}{2} \end{pmatrix} \implies \lambda = \frac{-1}{2} \pm \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} . $$

2.b)

PART 1:

Consider the highly coupled nonlinear system given by

$$ \begin{pmatrix} \dot x_1 \\ \dot x_2 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{1}{2}x_1 - x_2 - \frac{1}{2}x_1(x_1^2 + x_2^2) \\ \frac{1}{2}x_2 + x_1 - x_2(x_1^2 + x_2^2) \end{pmatrix} $$

which has a single equilibrium point at $\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix}^T$.

$$ J = \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{\partial (\frac{1}{2}x_1 - x_2 - \frac{1}{2}x_1(x_1^2 + x_2^2))}{\partial x_1} & \frac{\partial (\frac{1}{2}x_1 - x_2 - \frac{1}{2}x_1(x_1^2 + x_2^2))}{\partial x_2} \\ \frac{\partial (\frac{1}{2}x_2 + x_1 - x_2(x_1^2 + x_2^2))}{\partial x_1} & \frac{\partial (\frac{1}{2}x_2 + x_1 - x_2(x_1^2 + x_2^2))}{\partial x_2} \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} (\frac{1}{2} - \frac{3}{2}x_1^2 - x_2^2) & (-1 - 2x_1x_2) \\ (1 - x_1x_2) & (\frac{1}{2} - \frac{3}{2}x_2^2 + x_1^2) \end{pmatrix}. $$

Evaluating the linearized system at the fixed point gives us

$$ A = J(0,0) = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{1}{2} & -1 \\ 1 & \frac{1}{2} \end{pmatrix} \implies \lambda = \frac{1}{2} \pm i $$

which indicates an unstable spiral. But that's not the whole story!

PART 2:

Let's introduce polar coordinates. Let $r \geq 0$, $x_1 = r\cos{(\theta)}$, and $x_2 = r\sin{(\theta)}.$ Now let's choose $x_1$ and proceed to take the time derivative. We will equate it with the original dynamics, making the appropriate substitutions:

$$\begin{align} \dot x_1 &= \dot r \cos{(\theta)} - r\sin{(\theta)}\dot \theta \\ &= \frac{1}{2}r\cos{(\theta)} -\frac{1}{2}r^3\cos{(\theta)} - r\sin{(\theta)} \end{align} $$

Now we group the terms by factoring out $\cos{(\theta)}$ to get:

$$\dot r \cos{(\theta)} - r\sin{(\theta)}\dot \theta = \frac{1}{2}(r-r^3)\cos{(\theta)} - r\sin{(\theta)}(1)$$

This implies:

$$\begin{align} \dot r &= \frac{1}{2}r(1-r^2)\\ \dot \theta &= 1 \end{align}$$

The critical points are the origin and $r=1$ which corresponds to the unit circle in the phase plane.

Conclusions:

  • $\dot \theta =1 \implies$ All nonzero solutions spiral around the origin in the CCW direction.

  • $\dot r=\frac{1}{2}r(1-r^2) \implies \dot r = 0$ when $r=0,1$ and solutions on here stay on here.

  • $\dot r < 0$ when $r>1 \implies$ solutions outside of the unit circle spiral inward toward it.

  • $\dot r > 0$ when $r<1 \implies$ solutions inside of the unit circle spiral outward toward it.

def dynamics(initial, t):
    '''
    Assumes: initial is [r0, theta0] and t is the dummy variable of time instances
    Returns: the dynamics [r_dot, theta_dot]
    '''
    r0,t0 = initial
    r_dot = sm.Rational(1,2)*r0*(1 - r0**2) 
    theta_dot = 1
    return [r_dot, theta_dot]

# Set the time instances
t = np.linspace(0., 40, 6000)

# Plot several trajectories
for i in range(10):
    sol = spi.odeint(dynamics,[2-0.2*i, i*sm.pi/4], t); # integrate to get r and theta. Decrement to see the effects of different r
    plt.polar(sol[:,1], sol[:,0]) # Polar line plot
    plt.scatter(sol[0,1],sol[0,0]) # Plot the STARTING points so we can see which direction the curves take

# Plot the limit cycle in bold black
sol = spi.odeint(dynamics,[1,i], t)
plt.polar(sol[:,1], sol[:,0], c='k', lw=2.5)   
plt.title('Sample Trajectories')
plt.show()

4.b)

Recall that when $A \in \mathbb{R}^{n\times n}$, then the we define $e^{At}$ by

$$ e^{At} \triangleq I + At + \frac{(At)^2}{2!} + \frac{(At)^3}{3!} + \dots $$

First, we will prove that $(e^{At})^T = e^{A^Tt}$. Beginning with the infinite series definition:

$$ \begin{align} (e^{At})^T &= (\sum \limits_{n=0}^{\infty} (\frac{1}{n!} {(At)^n})^T \text{via definition} \\ &= \sum \limits_{n=0}^{\infty} (\frac{1}{n!} {(At)^n})^T \text{ commutes with addition}\\ &= \sum \limits_{n=0}^{\infty} \frac{1}{n!} ({(At)^n})^T \\ &= \sum \limits_{n=0}^{\infty} \frac{1}{n!} ({(At)^T})^n \text{commutes with powers} \\ &= \sum \limits_{n=0}^{\infty} \frac{1}{n!} ({A^Tt})^n \text{ since t$\in \mathbb{R}$}\\ &= e^{A^Tt}. \end{align}$$

Next, we will check if $[A^T,A]=0$ (i.e. $A^T$ commutes with $A$). If it does, we will leverage our result from HW4 to prove $e^{At}$ is an orthonormal matrix:

$$ [A,B]=0 \implies e^Ae^B = e^{A+B} = e^{B+A} = e^Be^A.$$
In [16]:
LHS = A.transpose() @ A
RHS = A @ A.transpose()
print(LHS == RHS)

$$\left ( \left[\begin{matrix}w_{2}^{2} + w_{3}^{2} & - w_{1} w_{2} & - w_{1} w_{3}\\- w_{1} w_{2} & w_{1}^{2} + w_{3}^{2} & - w_{2} w_{3}\\- w_{1} w_{3} & - w_{2} w_{3} & w_{1}^{2} + w_{2}^{2}\end{matrix}\right], \quad \left[\begin{matrix}w_{2}^{2} + w_{3}^{2} & - w_{1} w_{2} & - w_{1} w_{3}\\- w_{1} w_{2} & w_{1}^{2} + w_{3}^{2} & - w_{2} w_{3}\\- w_{1} w_{3} & - w_{2} w_{3} & w_{1}^{2} + w_{2}^{2}\end{matrix}\right]\right )$$

Since $[A^T,A]=0$, we can say that

$$e^{A^Tt}e^{At} = e^{(A^T + A)t} = e^{(-A + A)t} = e^O = I.$$

Thus, $e^{A^Tt}$ is an orthonormal matrix.

4.c)

An equilibrium point satisfies $\dot x = f(x) = Ax = 0$. So, if we can show

$$ Ax = A a \begin{pmatrix} w_1 \\ w_2 \\ w_3 \end{pmatrix} = a \begin{pmatrix} 0 & -w_3 & w_2 \\ w_3 & 0 & -w_1 \\ -w_2 & w_1 & 0 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} w_1 \\ w_2 \\ w_3 \end{pmatrix} =0 $$

then we can claim $x$ is an equilibrium point of the system for any $a\in\mathbb{R}.$ We verify the calculation in python.

def rotation_dynamics(X,t,a,b,c):
    '''
    Assumes: X is our initial conditions, 
             t is a dummy variable of time for our integrator,
             a,b,c are our values for w1,w2,w3
             
    Returns: the dynamics xdot, ydot, zdot
    '''
    x,y,z = X
    return [-c*y + b*z,
            -c*x - a*z,
            -b*x + a*y]

5. Analysis of a Bistable Switch¶

A genetic bistable switch has the model

$$ \dot u = \frac{\alpha_1}{1 + v^2} - u \\ \dot v = \frac{\alpha_2}{1 + u^2} - v $$

where $\alpha_1$ and $\alpha_2$ are the expression rates of the two proteins $u$ and $v$, and $\beta$ and $\gamma$ are the called Hill coefficients. The behavior of this system is that when one protein is high, the other should be low.

a) Show that when $\alpha_1 = \alpha_2 = \frac{17}{4}$ there are two isolated equilibra corresponding to having one protein be high and the other low. Show that these equilibria are stable. Also show that there number $q$ such that $u=v=q$ is an (un)stable equilibrium. Note: You might start this problem by plotting the vector field for this system and finding the equilibria graphically.

b) Find values of $\alpha_1$ and $\alpha_2$ for which there is only equilibrium (assuming positive values for $u$ and $v$). Is this equilibrium stable?

$\textbf{Grading breakdown:}$

3pts for finding the equilibria of the system, particularly [0.25,4.0] and [4.0,0.25]
2pts for using the eigenvalues of direction of the phase plot to show that these two equilibria are stable
2pts for finding a q such that q=u=v is not stable, but is a saddle point
2pts (b) for finding values of the alphas for which there is only one equilibrium
1pt (b) for stating the correct stability of this equilibrium

5.a)

Let's begin generally with the given dynamics:

$$ \dot u = \frac{\alpha_1}{1 + v^2} - u \\ \dot v = \frac{\alpha_2}{1 + u^2} - v. $$

Linearizing we find

$$ J = \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{\partial (\frac{\alpha_1}{1 + v^2} - u)}{\partial u} & \frac{\partial (\frac{\alpha_1}{1 + v^2} - u)}{\partial v} \\ \frac{\partial (\frac{\alpha_2}{1 + u^2} - v)}{\partial u} & \frac{\partial (\frac{\alpha_2}{1 + u^2} - v)}{\partial v} \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -1 & \frac{-2\alpha_1 v}{(1+v^2)^2} \\ \frac{-2\alpha_2 u}{(1+u^2)^2} & -1 \end{pmatrix} $$

5.b)

When $\alpha_1 = \alpha_2 = \alpha = u(1 + v^2)$ or $v(1 + u^2)$, then the only possilble equilibrium is $\bar x = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1\end{pmatrix}^T$. And in either case (the second is shown below)

$$ J(1,1)= \begin{pmatrix} \frac{2uv}{1+v^2} - 1 & \frac{-2v^2(1 + u^2)}{(1+v^2)^2} + \frac{1+u^2}{1+v^2} \\ 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix}\bigg \rvert_{\bar x} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix}.$$

The eigenvalues of $J(1,1)$ are $\lambda = 0,0$. Thus, this equilibrium is marginally stable.

6. Simulation¶

Using simulation and visualization, explain the behavior of the system

\begin{eqnarray} \dot x & = & -y - z \\ \dot y & = & x + a y \\ \dot z & = & b + z(x-c) \end{eqnarray}

where $a=0.2$, $b=0.2$ and $c=5.7$.

$\textbf{Grading breakdown:}$

3pts for defining the dynamics of the system
2pts for integrating the dynamics via odeint, an euler scheme, or some other scheme
2pts for providing a 3D plot or 2D slices
3pts for explaining the behavior of the system

6.)

This system is called the Rossler Chaotic Attractor, and its chaotic behavior is sensitive to initial conditions. We will use python to visualize the changes in behavior after slightly perturbing the inital conditions.

With these parameters it has two complex eigenvalues that make the attractor spiral outward in the xy plane. The last negative eigenvalue is responsible for the motion that occurs within the attractor on the z axis.

In [56]:
def Rossler(x, y, z, a, b, c):
    '''
    Assumes: x, y, z are spacial variables and a, b, c are constants
    Returns: the Rossler Chaotic attractor dynamics xdot, ydot, zdot 
    '''
    xdot = -y - z
    ydot = x + a*y
    zdot = b + z*(x - c)
    return xdot, ydot, zdot

def integrate_Rossler(x, y, z, a, b, c, n):
    '''
    Assumes: x, y, z are (n+1,) sized, initialized arrays and a, b, c are constants
    Returns: the solution to the Rossler dynamics x, y, z via Euler scheme
    '''
    for i in range(n):
        xdot, ydot, zdot = Rossler(x[i], y[i], z[i], a=a, b=b, c=c)
        x[i+1] = x[i] + xdot*dt
        y[i+1] = y[i] + ydot*dt
        z[i+1] = z[i] + zdot*dt
    return x, y, z
